==English==

===Etymology===
From the French ''-ette'', (the [[diminutive]], or otherwise, feminine form of the masculine suffix ''-et'')

===Suffix===
'''-ette'''

#Used to form [[noun]]s meaning a smaller form of something.
#:''[[cigarette]]''
#Used to form nouns meaning the female equivalent of.
#:''[[majorette]]'', ''[[bachelorette]]''
#Used to form nouns meaning an [[imitation]] or [[substitute]] of something.
#:''[[leatherette]]''
#Used to form nouns of a [[colloquial]] or [[humorous]] nature, which result in a lowering of status of women.
#:Example:  Calling a female Army Major, a "Majorette", or a female lawyer, a "lawyerette".

